{
  "slug": "joker-folie-a-deux-hates-you-will-you-return-the-favor",
  "title": "‘Joker: Folie à Deux’ Hates You. Will You Return the Favor?",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Van Lathan"
  ],
  "published": "2024-10-04",
  "runtimeMin": 106,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Van Lathan on why Todd Phillips' 'Joker: Folie à Deux' plays like a rebuke to everyone who loved the first one, then a long argument about movie discourse and what an audience is owed. Plus: Sean interviews Greg Jardin about 'It's What's Inside.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Joker: Folie à Deux'",
      "note": "With Van Lathan",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Joker: Folie à Deux",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Todd Phillips' musical follow-up, Scott Silver co-writing, Joaquin Phoenix back as Arthur Fleck with Lady Gaga as Harley Quinn, Brendan Gleeson, Catherine Keener, Harry Lawtey as Harvey Dent, and Steve Coogan. Set two years on, mostly a courtroom drama scored to mid-century standards (Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered; That's Entertainment; For Once in My Life). Van 'doesn't get it'; both read the ending as Phillips punishing the audience that mythologized the first film, Arthur rejecting the Joker gang and dying alone with no larger meaning. Van's verdict: 'well-made, not good movie.' Sean: 'this guy fucking hates me,' respects it, doesn't like it. Gaga ends up inconsequential."
        },
        {
          "title": "Joker",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The Oscar-winning original they keep measuring against. Sean liked it and read it as a movie about 2019 America; Van never did, would rather watch 'There Will Be Blood' than see that tone in his Batman world. The sequel reads as Phillips' answer to everyone who called the first film an incel manifesto."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "What is an audience owed?",
      "note": "Movie discourse, rage-bait, and the 'fuck you' movie",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Requiem for a Dream",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "Van's model of a 'fuck you' movie that still hands you something sober about the world; Sean calls it the better film but a similar bottomless-pit-of-frustrated-morality shape."
        },
        {
          "title": "Se7en",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Sean's example of an ending that leaves you asking what you learned, but with morality and procedure to hold onto. Van: the whole film is a guy insisting he wants to see how bad it gets, then finding out he can't handle it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Synecdoche, New York",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "The 'scooped out but worth it' comparison, about the performance of life and going through the motions. Watch it when you're in a good place in your life."
        },
        {
          "title": "Vice",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Van's 'not quite' benchmark: a director stepping out of comedy, good performances, a clear point, and still not sure it earned the runtime, same feeling he had walking out of Joker."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Big Short",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The McKay dramatic turn that landed, cited as the before to Vice's after."
        },
        {
          "title": "Don't Look Up",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Sean plays defender: the comedy is the weak part, but the closing turn toward appreciating your own life hit him at the right time. Folie à Deux has no such turn."
        },
        {
          "title": "Killers of the Flower Moon",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The green-room argument before a live Rewatchables: Van admits going in looking for reasons not to like it because of Scorsese's Marvel comments, then reckoning with a blank-check movie that did exactly what it wanted."
        },
        {
          "title": "Megalopolis",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The recurring example of a grand swing whose discourse arrived years before the movie, and which has become a litmus test for whether you're a good person just for buying a ticket."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Substance",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Named among the year's movies people were being put 'under the microscope' over."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Greg Jardin on 'It's What's Inside'",
      "guest": "Greg Jardin on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "It's What's Inside",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jardin's feature debut, a noisy Sundance acquisition Netflix won in a 36-hour bidding war for roughly five million, twice its budget. A one-location, one-night, eight-way body-swap sci-fi thriller with jokes, lit like horror (Argento's 'Suspiria' the touchstone). Shot draft 17 in Portland after a week of rehearsal where the cast read first from their souls, then from their bodies. Jardin, a longtime Netflix-promo director, edited and did the VFX himself; David Thompson's turn as Forbes was the hard one to cast and the film's pivot."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
